[2] Japan (Okinawa): US military
Date: Tue 14 Jul 2020
Source: XInhua News Agency [abridged, edited]
http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-07/14/c_139212533.htm


The Tokyo metropolitan government on Tuesday [14 Jul 2020] confirmed 143 new COVID-19 infections, with the number staying below the 200-mark for the 2nd day in a row but spiking above the 119 cases reported a day earlier. The previous day's figure marked the 1st time the number of daily COVID-19 cases had dropped below 200 in 5 days. Concerns remain about a resurgence of the virus, however, as clusters of infections have continued to occur at nighttime entertainment establishments in downtown areas in Tokyo including those in Shinjuku and Ikebukuro wards.

Localized clusters on US bases in Japan's southernmost prefecture of Okinawa have also triggered concerns, with Japan urging the United States to step up measures to stem the spread, the Foreign Ministry here said on Tuesday [14 Jul 2020].

The metropolitan government said that as for the newly detected cases in the capital, 93 people were aged in their 20s and 30s, with the infection route known in 79 cases, but unknown in 64. Employees or customers of nighttime entertainment establishments comprised 23 of the total new COVID-19 infections.

Tokyo's cumulative number of infections now stands at 8189, the highest among Japan's 47 prefectures, and accounting for more than one-third of the country's total COVID-19 cases. Nationwide, 330 new COVID-19 infections were detected, according to the latest figures on Tuesday evening [14 Jul 2020]. Aside from the cases in Tokyo, its neighboring prefectures of Saitama and Kanagawa confirmed 42 and 28 new cases respectively. Japan's cumulative total now stands at 22 583 COVID-19 cases. The nation's total death toll from the virus stands at 997 people, Tuesday evening's official figures showed.

The Japanese government on Tuesday [14 Jul 2020] requested the US to up its efforts to prevent the spread of the virus amid a recent spike in cases on US military bases in Okinawa. According to the prefectural government, around 100 COVID-19 cases have been reported on US bases in Okinawa sparking local and nationwide concern over the further spread of the virus.

Okinawa has reported very few cases of the coronavirus, [apart from] those related to US bases, since the outbreak began. Hence, local officials and residents have voiced strong concern that a further rise in COVID-19 cases on the island would devastate the region's local industries, especially as Japan is looking to ease international travel restrictions.

Japan's entry ban in place for 129 countries and regions including the United States amid the pandemic does not apply to US military personnel under a status of forces agreement. A local hotel in the southern prefecture being used by US Marines and their families arriving in Japan from overseas to quarantine has also added to rising concerns over the virus' spread, the prefectural government said.

According to Japanese defense minister Taro Kono, there have been "several problems" regarding the US military's virus prevention measures. Okinawa governor Denny Tamaki said that some US military-linked personnel had held parties in downtown areas and on beaches in the prefecture, coinciding with Independence Day celebrations held on [4 Jul 2020].

The US Marine Corps Air Station Futenma has reported the most coronavirus cases at 71 infections as of Tuesday evening [14 Jul 2020], while 22 infections have been detected at Camp Hansen.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka

[According to the most recent Worldometer data on the USA reporting entities, as of 14 Jul 2020, the US military has reported 25 822 cases of COVID-19 (see section [3] E below for tables). A delicate situation is described in the above media report. Given the known situation that the USA has the highest total case count, plus the highest daily newly confirmed case counts, it does potentially pose a threat of transmission internationally when troops are deployed.

A map of Japan showing prefectures can be seen at https://www.digi-joho.com/japan-maps.html and a HealthMap/ProMED map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7576001,156. Okinawa is in the extreme south of the country, closer to Taiwan than Tokyo. - Mod.MPP]

