communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to the data on the Worldometer website, the total number of reported cases of COVID-19 worldwide is now 13 454 490, with reports of cases by 217 countries and territories worldwide. The global case count rose by 1.7% in the past 24 hours. The USA and Brazil are still the most severely affected countries in terms of cumulative case counts. In the past 24 hours though, the USA reported the most newly confirmed cases (65 594) followed by Brazil (43 245) and India (29 842). It is sobering to tally the total cumulative case counts for the top 5 countries (USA, Brazil, India, Russia, and Peru), and see that they represent over half of the total cases reported globally (55.7%). A global total of 581 118 deaths have been reported, an increase of 5593 deaths in the past 24 hours.

In descending rank order, the USA is number 1 for the number of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours, followed by Brazil, India, South Africa, Mexico, Russia, Colombia, Peru, Argentina, and Bangladesh. The same 10 countries as yesterday (13 Jul 2020), in a slightly different order. All these countries are currently experiencing major community-based transmission and considered global hot spots. The range in the top 10 daily newly confirmed cases goes from 3163 to 65 594. The number of daily newly confirmed cases is climbing rapidly in the USA. Noteworthy is that Kazakhstan is in the top 20 (number 15), having reported 1856 newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours. Also worthy of note is that 6 out of the top 10 countries for daily reported newly confirmed cases are from the Americas region, consistent with the continued dominance of SARS-CoV-2 activity.

Impression: The SARS-CoV-2 is still actively being transmitted in all regions of the world, and many countries are showing increases in their daily newly confirmed case counts. - Mod.MPP]
